Not exactly. We are currently in what's known as an "inter-glacial period." That is a period where atmospheric temperature is increasing, and so glaciers and ice sheets are shrinking. Glacial and inter-glacial periods are normal during an ice age (which itself is defined as a period where the atmospheric temperature allows for continental and polar ice sheets and alpine glaciers to exist). We aren't in a "second ice age" because we haven't yet left the most recent one. Ice ages have come and gone throughout the history of the planet, but it's usually some kind of catastrophic change that triggers them to either start or stop. Sudden volcanic activity, a large asteroid impact, the evolution of photosynthetic life, etc. That said, when the earth is _in_ an ice age, there is a pattern when it comes to glacial and inter-glacial periods. It's a very regular cycle where the earth's atmosphere warms and cools in a predictable pattern. That is, until very recently. The atmosphere is warming far faster than it has in the past, and that rate of warming just so happens to coincide with the industrial revolution, where human beings started to release vast amounts of insulating gasses into the atmosphere. That's probably not a coincidence. And, more importantly, it's a serious problem. We might be leaving the current ice age, but human beings are definitely the cause. It's not "natural." Rates of environmental change matter. If changes happen too quickly, species cannot adapt fast enough and they die out. If a species that dies out happens to be critical to the ecosystem it resides in, the whole ecosystem could collapse, causing more species to go extinct, which leads to even more species going extinct and so on and so forth. If that happens on a global scale, it's what's known as a mass extinction event. And although it's unlikely that such an event would lead to the extinction of _all_ life from the planet, there's a very good chance that the human species would not survive. Entering or leaving an ice age is not typically good for most species. So, if humans are causing us to leave the current ice age, it's in our best interest to stop doing what we're doing to warm up the atmosphere.

Simple. there is a 60 year cycle of warming and cooling that has been measured around the world for over 170 years. Starting in 1850 to 1880 there was a warming period.
